==== Disaster Recovery Scenarios ====

Scenario 1: Single Service Corrupted

Example: Gitea database corrupted, service won't start

RTO: 30 minutes
RPO: 24 hours (last daily backup)

Recovery Procedure:

1. Identify corrupted service:
docker ps -a | grep gitea
docker logs gitea

2. Stop service:
docker compose stop gitea

3. Restore from most recent backup:
docker exec -i postgres psql -U gitea gitea < /opt/backups/gitea-db-[latest].sql

4. Restart service:
docker compose up -d gitea

5. Verify functionality:
curl http://git.lab.local

Expected downtime: 15-30 minutes
Data loss: Up to 24 hours (since last backup)

Scenario 2: VM Crashed (Cannot Boot)

Example: apps.lab.local won't boot after power failure

RTO: 1 hour
RPO: 1 week (last VM snapshot) + 24 hours (daily backups)

Recovery Procedure:

1. Attempt to restore VM from Proxmox snapshot:
- Proxmox UI → apps.lab.local → Snapshots → Rollback to latest

2. If snapshot restore successful:
- Boot VM
- Verify services: docker ps
- Restore data from daily backups (for data newer than snapshot)

3. If snapshot restore fails:
- Create new VM with same specs
- Install OS (Ubuntu 24.04)
- Restore /opt/docker from backup
- Restore docker-compose.yml
- Run: docker compose up -d

Expected downtime: 1-2 hours
Data loss: 24 hours (daily backup interval)

Scenario 3: Multiple VMs Down (Entire Proxmox Host Failed)

Example: Proxmox server hardware failure, all VMs offline

RTO: 4-8 hours
RPO: 24 hours

Recovery Procedure:

1. Obtain replacement hardware (or rebuild Proxmox host)

2. Install Proxmox on new hardware

3. Recreate VMs using documented specs:
- mgmt.lab.local: 3GB RAM, 2 vCPU, 30GB disk, Rocky Linux
- apps.lab.local: 10GB RAM, 4 vCPU, 100GB disk, Ubuntu
- mntr.lab.local: 3GB RAM, 2 vCPU, 50GB disk, Ubuntu

4. Install OS on each VM

5. Restore from backups (if backups stored offsite or on separate drive):

On mgmt.lab.local:
- Restore /opt/ansible
- Restore FreeIPA: ipa-restore

On apps.lab.local:
- Restore /opt/docker
- Restore databases
- Start services: docker compose up -d

On mntr.lab.local:
- Restore /opt/docker
- Restore Prometheus/Grafana/Loki data
- Start services: docker compose up -d

6. Verify all services:
- DNS resolution working
- Services accessible
- Monitoring operational

Expected downtime: 6-12 hours (depends on hardware availability)
Data loss: 24 hours (or more if offsite backups not current)

Critical dependency: Offsite backups (Phase 5) - without this, recovery impossible

Scenario 4: Complete Data Center Loss (Fire, Flood, Theft)

Example: Physical location destroyed, all hardware lost

RTO: 24-48 hours
RPO: 24 hours (if offsite backups configured)

Recovery Procedure:

Prerequisites (Phase 5 required):
- Offsite backups in cloud storage
- Documentation stored in Git repository (GitHub/GitLab)
- Encrypted backup copies

Recovery Steps:

1. Obtain new hardware

2. Download documentation from Git repository

3. Rebuild Proxmox host

4. Recreate VMs from documentation

5. Download backups from cloud storage

6. Decrypt backups:
gpg –decrypt backup.tar.gz.gpg > backup.tar.gz

7. Restore all services following documented procedures

8. Verify complete functionality

Expected downtime: 24-72 hours (depends on hardware procurement)
Data loss: 24 hours (if offsite backups current)

Current status: NOT RECOVERABLE - offsite backups not yet implemented
Action required: Implement Phase 5 (Offsite Backup Strategy)

==== RTO/RPO Targets ====

Recovery Time Objective (RTO): Maximum acceptable downtime
Recovery Point Objective (RPO): Maximum acceptable data loss

Critical Services (Tier 0):

Services: FreeIPA, DNS
Importance: Authentication and name resolution - entire lab depends on these

RTO: 30 minutes
RPO: 24 hours

Backup frequency: Daily + weekly
Restore priority: FIRST

Application Services (Tier 1):

Services: Gitea, WordPress, Nginx
Importance: User-facing applications with business value

RTO: 2 hours
RPO: 24 hours

Backup frequency: Daily
Restore priority: SECOND

Monitoring Services (Tier 2):

Services: Prometheus, Grafana, Loki
Importance: Operational visibility - helpful but not critical

RTO: 4 hours
RPO: 7 days (acceptable metric/log data loss)

Backup frequency: Daily (but can tolerate data loss)
Restore priority: THIRD

Development/Test Services (Tier 3):

Services: Minecraft, test containers
Importance: Non-critical, recreational

RTO: 8 hours
RPO: 7 days

Backup frequency: Weekly
Restore priority: LAST

RTO/RPO by Scenario:

Scenario 	RTO 	RPO 	Priority
Single service failure 	30 min 	24 hrs 	High
VM crash 	1 hour 	24 hrs 	High
Proxmox host failure 	8 hours 	24 hrs 	Medium
Data center loss 	48 hours 	24 hrs 	Low


