==== Troubleshooting Backups ====

Backup file is 0 bytes or missing:

Diagnosis:
ls -lh /opt/backups/[service]-*
# Shows 0 byte file or file doesn't exist

Cause: Backup command failed silently

Solution:
# Run backup command manually with error output:
docker exec postgres pg_dump -U gitea gitea > /tmp/test.sql 2>&1
cat /tmp/test.sql
# Look for error messages

# Common issues:
# - Wrong database name
# - Wrong username/password
# - Database not running
# - Permission denied

Fix underlying issue, then re-run backup

Backup directory doesn't exist:

Diagnosis:
ls /opt/backups
# No such file or directory

Cause: Directory not created

Solution:
mkdir -p /opt/backups
sudo chown [user]:[user] /opt/backups

Permission denied errors:

Diagnosis:
ls -ld /opt/backups
# Shows: drwxr-xr-x root root

Cause: Wrong ownership

Solution:
sudo chown jireland:jireland /opt/backups
sudo chmod 755 /opt/backups

Database dump fails:

Diagnosis:
docker exec postgres pg_dump -U gitea gitea
# Error: authentication failed

Cause: Wrong credentials or database name

Solution:
# Test connection first:
docker exec -it postgres psql -U gitea gitea
# Should connect without errors

# If fails, check docker-compose.yml for correct credentials

Disk space full:

Diagnosis:
df -h /opt/backups
# Shows: 100% used

Cause: Old backups not cleaned up, or backups too large

Solution:
# Delete old backups manually:
find /opt/backups -type f -mtime +7 -delete

# Or delete specific large files:
ls -lhS /opt/backups/
# Shows largest files first
rm /opt/backups/[large-old-file]

# Check if backups are unexpectedly large:
du -sh /opt/backups/*
# Investigate any anomalies

Ansible playbook fails:

Diagnosis:
ansible-playbook backup-homelab.yml
# Shows: FAILED - RETRYING or fatal errors

Solution:
# Run with verbose output:
ansible-playbook backup-homelab.yml -vvv

# Check for:
# - SSH connectivity issues
# - Sudo permission problems
# - Disk space issues on target VMs
# - Service not running

# Fix identified issue and re-run

Restore fails - “file exists”:

Diagnosis:
tar -xzf backup.tar.gz -C /opt/docker
# Error: file exists

Cause: Trying to restore over existing data

Solution:
# Backup current state first (just in case):
mv /opt/docker/[service] /opt/docker/[service].old

# Then extract:
tar -xzf backup.tar.gz -C /opt/docker

# After verifying restore worked:
rm -rf /opt/docker/[service].old

Restore succeeds but service won't start:

Diagnosis:
docker compose up -d [service]
docker logs [service]
# Shows errors

Possible causes:
- Permissions wrong after restore
- Config file corrupted
- Database connection failed
- Port conflict

Solutions:
# Fix permissions:
sudo chown -R jireland:jireland /opt/docker/[service]

# Check config syntax:
cat /opt/docker/[service]/config.yml

# Verify dependencies running:
docker ps | grep postgres

# Check ports:
ss -tlnp | grep [port]

==== Offsite Backup Strategy (Future - Phase 5) ====

Current Status: NOT IMPLEMENTED
Target Date: Phase 5.1 (Estimated: August 2026)

Planned Implementation:

Phase 5.1 - External USB Backup:

Hardware:
- 2TB USB 3.0 external drive
- LUKS encrypted
- Mounted at /mnt/backup on mgmt.lab.local

Process:
1. Daily backups run to /opt/backups (as current)
2. Weekly sync to USB drive
3. 30-day retention on USB drive

Commands:
# Encrypt drive (one-time setup):
sudo cryptsetup luksFormat /dev/sdb1
sudo cryptsetup luksOpen /dev/sdb1 backup-drive
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/mapper/backup-drive

# Mount drive:
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/backup
sudo mount /dev/mapper/backup-drive /mnt/backup

# Sync backups weekly:
rsync -av /opt/backups/ /mnt/backup/$(date +%Y-%m-%d)/

Phase 5.2 - Cloud Offsite Backup:

Provider: Backblaze B2 or AWS S3
Retention: 90 days
Cost: $5-10/month

Process:
1. Encrypt backups before upload
2. Upload to cloud storage
3. Verify upload successful
4. Maintain 90-day retention in cloud

Commands:
# Install rclone:
sudo apt install rclone

# Configure remote (one-time):
